import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy import interpolate

x = np.array(df_6[100:110]['t']) #np.arange(0, 2*np.pi+np.pi/4, 2*np.pi/8)
y = np.array(df_6[100:110]['ax'])
tck = interpolate.splrep(x, y, s=1)
xnew = df_6[100:110]['t'] # np.arange(0, 2*np.pi, np.pi/50)
ynew = interpolate.splev(xnew, tck, der=0)

plt.figure()
plt.plot(x, y, 'x', xnew, ynew, x, y, 'b')
plt.legend(['Linear', 'Cubic Spline', 'True'])
#plt.axis([-0.05, 6.33, -1.05, 1.05])
plt.title('Cubic-spline interpolation')
plt.show()

from geomdl import fitting
from geomdl.visualization import VisMPL as vis
import itertools 

x = np.array(df_6[11:110]['t'])
y = np.array(df_6[11:110]['ax'])
x -= x[0]
#tmp = dict(itertools.product(x, y)) 
# The NURBS Book Ex9.1
#points = ((0, 0), (3, 4), (-1, 4), (-4, 0), (-4, -3))
degree = 2  # cubic curve
tmp = list(zip(x, y))
# Do global curve interpolation
curve = fitting.approximate_curve(tmp, degree)

# Plot the interpolated curve
curve.delta = 0.01
curve.vis = vis.VisCurve2D()
curve.render()

print(np.mean(minta_v))
print(np.min(minta_v))

data = minta_v
density = gaussian_kde(data)
xs = np.linspace(0,0.05,200)
density.covariance_factor = lambda : .25
density._compute_covariance()
plt.plot(xs,density(xs))
